01:35.714 --> 01:43.825
Last week we started a new series here at Riverview, a Christmas series where we are looking at the various names and titles of Jesus given throughout the Christmas narrative.

01:43.865 --> 01:54.020
And last Sunday, we spent time not in a traditional Christmas passage, but we were in John chapter one because we were looking at Jesus as the son of God.

01:54.661 --> 01:59.207
And as we did that first, we saw many aspects of his deity.

01:59.848 --> 02:04.274
John began his gospel account with how Jesus is and has always been eternal.

02:04.770 --> 02:13.363
that Jesus was the incarnate word, that all things were created through him, that in him was life, and how that life was the light of men.

02:13.984 --> 02:23.618
But the verse that most resonated with the Christmas story that we are familiar with was John chapter one verse 14, where it says that the word became flesh and dwelt among us.

02:24.820 --> 02:31.730
The Christmas story celebrates this truth that God entered the world, and that he lived amongst those that he had created.

02:32.386 --> 02:37.392
Now that winter night in Bethlehem, God arrived in creation as a baby born to human parents.

02:38.072 --> 02:44.780
And this belief, this aspect of the Christmas story, it is essential to our lives as followers of Jesus.

02:45.701 --> 02:59.276
Compared to other prominent religions, the truth of the incarnation that God entered the world as a human being, it is a core foundational belief that we hold that is actually exclusive to Christianity.

02:59.296 --> 03:01.138
And it's a truth that is so important

03:01.730 --> 03:05.876
that if you lose it, then you lose Christianity altogether.

03:06.597 --> 03:11.325
You don't have our faith without the truth that we are looking at today.

03:12.306 --> 03:15.651
Well, John's gospel began by showing us that Jesus truly is the Son of God.

03:15.671 --> 03:22.642
This morning, we're going to see in another gospel account how Jesus was and is at the same time, the Son of man.

03:23.458 --> 03:30.485
And as we see this truth throughout the scripture this morning, we're also gonna spend time looking at why it matters so much for us in our faith today.

03:30.525 --> 03:34.209
So if you have a Bible with you, you can go ahead and open it up to Matthew chapter one.

03:34.229 --> 03:38.333
We're gonna be jumping around the scriptures today, but we're gonna start in Matthew chapter one.

03:39.074 --> 03:42.798
Matthew is the first book in the New Testament, so it's about three-fourths of the way through your Bible.

03:42.818 --> 03:50.546
Your Bible is an Old Testament, which was the scriptures before Jesus was in the world as a human being, and then the New Testament is after that.

03:50.946 --> 03:52.588
And this is the first gospel account.

03:52.628 --> 03:57.113
It was written by Matthew and who, like John last week, was also one of the disciples.

03:57.534 --> 04:02.620
So this is a firsthand account, but Matthew's gospel begins much differently than John did.

04:02.660 --> 04:05.243
Well, John was really broad and focused on the macro.

04:05.564 --> 04:11.671
The big picture, Matthew gets into the weeds right away of Jesus' family line.

04:12.112 --> 04:20.722
We see this starting in Matthew chapter one, verse one, where it says this, an account of the genealogy of Jesus Christ, the son of David, the son of Abraham.

04:21.090 --> 04:22.852
Abraham fathered Isaac.

04:22.872 --> 04:24.074
Isaac fathered Jacob.

04:24.575 --> 04:26.237
Jacob fathered Judah and his brothers.

04:26.818 --> 04:29.342
Judah fathered Perez and Zara by Tamar.

04:29.882 --> 04:31.044
Perez fathered Hezrin.

04:31.204 --> 04:32.426
Hezrin fathered Aram.

04:32.846 --> 04:34.288
Aram fathered Aminadab.

04:34.549 --> 04:36.171
Aminadab fathered nation.

04:36.592 --> 04:37.753
Nation fathered Salmon.

04:38.554 --> 04:40.457
Salmon fathered Boaz by Rahab.

04:40.858 --> 04:43.021
Boaz fathered Obid by Ruth.

04:43.602 --> 04:47.086
Obid fathered Jesse and Jesse fathered King David.

04:47.807 --> 04:49.650
Okay, we're gonna stop the genealogy there.

04:50.402 --> 04:59.897
But the first lines of books or accounts are always really important because with the first words, you can kind of see what the author is trying to communicate and the foundation that they're laying to do so.

05:00.498 --> 05:07.649
Last week, the first three words of John's gospel account were in the beginning because he took us back to the book of Genesis.

05:08.030 --> 05:11.435
And because his goal was to show how Jesus was eternal, right?

05:11.475 --> 05:15.181
How he was everlasting, how he was the light of the world, the son of God.

05:15.401 --> 05:18.546
Matthew chooses to begin his gospel differently.

05:18.882 --> 05:25.128
with a list of 45 unique names, many of which are very difficult to pronounce.

05:25.288 --> 05:36.418
So kudos to Shauna for crushing it this morning, but the first lines of the gospel account are this, an account of the genealogy of Jesus Christ, son of David, son of Abraham.

05:37.239 --> 05:40.022
So the question for us today is why would Matthew do this?

05:40.923 --> 05:44.446
Why would he start his account with a list of names?

05:45.447 --> 05:48.850
Because genealogies are not the most interesting thing to read.

05:48.994 --> 05:49.835
Right?

05:49.895 --> 05:51.497
Especially for us modern readers.

05:51.557 --> 05:58.466
If you've ever done a Bible reading plan or whenever you get to this section of Scripture, you usually skim it or you skip it altogether.

05:58.947 --> 06:04.955
Because the names are really hard to read and they don't really mean much to us if we don't do a deeper dive into who the actual people were.

06:05.595 --> 06:08.579
But Matthew was really intentional in doing this this way.

06:09.020 --> 06:13.906
Because his goal was to show how Jesus was a human being.

06:14.562 --> 06:20.089
And now he was the fulfillment of what the Old Testament said about a Messiah coming to rescue his people.

06:21.150 --> 06:24.314
It's really helpful for us to know who Matthew's primary audience was.

06:24.835 --> 06:28.359
It was to Jews who knew what the Old Testament Scriptures said.

06:29.080 --> 06:40.114
So what Matthew was doing is who was going back to the Old Testament to show how all these prophecies that God had given his people throughout the centuries, they had all led up to Jesus.

06:41.090 --> 06:48.465
By going into the family line, he's communicating that at the same time, Jesus was both fully divine and fully human.

06:49.887 --> 06:58.144
Even though we often skip these lists of names in the scriptures, it's really important for us that they're there because they are a record of history.

06:58.545 --> 07:01.330
These are real people who existed in real time.

07:02.082 --> 07:06.048
Earlier this year, I was given a gift by my aunt Alice, me and my siblings.

07:06.068 --> 07:11.075
We were given this folder, and it was actually a genealogy of the maternal side of our family.

07:12.056 --> 07:17.744
And it was pictures, and it was records of family members that I had never even seen before.

07:17.864 --> 07:18.645
I didn't even know.

07:18.665 --> 07:21.810
I had seen pictures of people in my family from the 1800s.

07:21.950 --> 07:26.096
And as I flipped through this folder, I was just blown away.

07:26.717 --> 07:29.380
Because I saw pictures of my great, great grandparents.

07:29.401 --> 07:30.482
I learned who they were.

07:30.882 --> 07:34.147
where they lived, what they cared about, the struggles and the victories that they had.

07:34.908 --> 07:39.315
And what happened, this was one of the most profound and powerful gifts I've ever gotten.

07:40.397 --> 07:46.106
Because I not only had a greater understanding of my family, but my love for my family grew as well.

07:46.867 --> 07:48.249
Because I knew them more deeply.

07:49.071 --> 07:50.613
See, that's what genealogies do.

07:51.675 --> 07:56.402
They help show us history, real people who lived and experiences that they had.

07:57.250 --> 08:02.538
And when we look at the genealogy in Matthew, we actually see some names we may recognize.

08:02.618 --> 08:05.903
If you've read some of the Old Testament, first we see the name Abraham.

08:06.724 --> 08:12.313
Back in Genesis chapter 12, Abraham, he was this man that God had chosen to bless and make a covenant with.

08:13.054 --> 08:18.242
God said that he would bless him with land and descendants and blessing and nothing about Abraham warranted this choice.

08:18.903 --> 08:21.747
Okay, people didn't turn in their resumes to God and say, all right, pick me.

08:22.489 --> 08:26.034
It was just out of nowhere that God said, Abraham, I am gonna pick you.

08:27.266 --> 08:35.998
It was only through God's generosity and His grace that He chose Him to bring about a nation of people, to bring about a Savior into the world.

08:36.038 --> 08:38.681
And the rest of the book of Genesis is about this family.

08:38.722 --> 08:41.605
We see other names like Isaac and Jacob and Judah.

08:42.286 --> 08:45.210
But then generations later, we see other names we may recognize.

08:45.731 --> 08:50.898
Names like Rahab and Boaz and Ruth, if you were with us this past summer,

08:51.202 --> 08:53.064
We did a series here called Testify.

08:53.084 --> 08:54.866
You can find all these messages online.

08:55.527 --> 08:59.191
But what we did was we looked at faith stories of prominent men and women in the Bible.

08:59.211 --> 09:01.033
And two of the stories we looked at were these women.

09:01.774 --> 09:03.536
We looked at Rahab and we looked at Ruth.

09:04.396 --> 09:10.323
Rahab was a Canaanite woman that protected the Jewish spies that snuck into Jericho back in the book of Joshua.

09:10.483 --> 09:12.926
This is Joshua chapter two through Joshua six.

09:13.566 --> 09:20.434
And because of her faith, she and her family were spared and they lived amongst the Jews after this.

09:21.122 --> 09:25.507
And as this happened, Rahab actually married a Jewish man and had a son named Boaz.

09:26.388 --> 09:27.890
Boaz shows up in the book of Ruth.

09:28.231 --> 09:34.118
He marries Ruth and redeems her after she has this really difficult life and a lot of grief going on.

09:34.658 --> 09:39.144
But then the genealogy continues to show that Ruth is the grandmother of King David.

09:40.305 --> 09:46.593
Both Rahab and Ruth are remembered in the scriptures for their great faith amidst harrowing life circumstances.

09:47.874 --> 09:49.937
We could spend all day in this genealogy.

09:49.957 --> 09:51.058
We're not gonna do that.

09:51.362 --> 10:00.033
Because all throughout this list, though, there is an amazing legacy, a legacy of ordinary people that God chose to work through in history.

10:00.894 --> 10:06.361
And it was through this family line that Jesus would enter the world as the Son of Man.

10:07.543 --> 10:09.946
We see that Son of Man title show up in other places.

10:09.986 --> 10:13.330
And more in the Old Testament, it's used in a general sense.

10:13.570 --> 10:20.160
Like a human being, if you're a man, you're a son of man, or if you're a woman, you're a daughter of man, right, can be in a general sense.

10:20.180 --> 10:23.505
But Jesus would refer to himself as the son of man.

10:24.486 --> 10:28.532
This was actually his favorite way to talk about himself in the scriptures.

10:29.013 --> 10:37.626
While other people would refer to Jesus as the Christ or the Messiah, when they were recognizing him and said, Jesus called himself son of man more than anything else.

10:38.287 --> 10:40.530
It shows up 80 times in the New Testament.

10:40.738 --> 10:44.222
over 30 times it showed up in the Gospel of Matthew alone.

10:45.383 --> 10:55.655
And as this title, it would have resonated with the original readers of Matthew because they would have heard it before, or they would have read it and think, thought, where have I seen that?

10:56.716 --> 10:57.657
Does that ever happen to you?

10:58.458 --> 11:05.266
You hear a line from a movie, right, or a song lyric, or you hear a name and you know you've heard it before, but you can't quite place it.

11:05.858 --> 11:07.741
When that happens to me, it bothers me.

11:08.522 --> 11:10.285
So I have to look it up on my phone.

11:10.305 --> 11:13.830
But before we had smartphones, it would just stay in my brain.

11:14.311 --> 11:17.055
But then it would come to me hours later, right?

11:17.095 --> 11:19.119
I would be like talking with someone and I'd be like, Tom Hanks!

11:20.601 --> 11:22.424
And they'd be like, what?

11:23.505 --> 11:25.589
Because a normal person, they had moved on.

11:26.310 --> 11:28.633
But for me, my brain doesn't work like that.

11:28.894 --> 11:31.097
It gets stuck with meaningless information.

11:32.079 --> 11:34.162
But for the readers of Matthew's gospel,

11:34.626 --> 11:39.914
They would have read Son of Man over 30 times and they wouldn't have actually wondered where it was from.

11:39.974 --> 11:52.935
They would have known right away because one of their prophets had a vision hundreds of years earlier that used that exact title for someone who would come in the future.

11:53.876 --> 11:55.539
This prophet was named Daniel.

11:56.661 --> 12:02.450
As a teenager, Daniel was a Jewish man enslaved along with his people by the enemy nation of Babylon.

12:02.658 --> 12:04.922
You can read all about this in the Old Testament in the book of Daniel.

12:05.543 --> 12:08.848
And this happened about 600 years before Jesus was born.

12:09.589 --> 12:13.776
And while Daniel was in service to this enemy king, he had this terrifying vision.

12:14.437 --> 12:22.010
And in this vision, there were these four massive beasts that came out of the sea and these beasts, they represented these evil human kingdoms that would come to exist.

12:22.090 --> 12:29.522
But in the middle of this vision, a person shows up on the clouds of heaven, one like the son of man.

12:29.922 --> 12:31.724
Look at what Daniel saw in his vision.

12:31.744 --> 12:33.346
This is Daniel seven verse 13.

12:34.307 --> 12:39.774
I continued watching in the night visions and suddenly one like a son of man was coming with the clouds of heaven.

12:39.794 --> 12:42.477
He approached the ancient of days and was escorted before him.

12:43.078 --> 12:49.366
He was given dominion and glory and a kingdom so that those of every people, nation and language should serve him.

12:50.067 --> 12:57.155
His dominion is an everlasting dominion that will not pass away and his kingdom is one that will not be destroyed.

12:58.277 --> 12:59.378
So in this vision,

12:59.938 --> 13:08.027
This terrifying vision, Daniel sees a human being appear out of the sky, but this man is different than other people.

13:08.788 --> 13:13.173
He approached the ancient of days, God the Father with boldness.

13:14.355 --> 13:18.039
This man was given dominion and glory and a kingdom.

13:18.299 --> 13:22.884
Every people, nation and language would serve him and his kingdom would be everlasting.

13:24.586 --> 13:27.730
This prophetic vision would have been known

13:28.514 --> 13:32.239
to first century Jewish people, because it was part of their scriptures.

13:33.301 --> 13:35.965
Daniel was a well-known figure in their history.

13:36.786 --> 13:40.491
This was something they were looking forward to, a son of man coming.

13:41.492 --> 13:47.661
So as Jesus would use this title for himself, he would be communicating the truth of who he was.

13:47.961 --> 13:48.562
It was him.

13:48.622 --> 13:52.688
He was the person they were waiting for.

13:54.250 --> 13:56.914
But not everyone believed that, unfortunately.

13:57.922 --> 14:09.234
But as we open the scripture and we look at the life Jesus lived in the gospels, we see that even though he was the son of God, he truly was a son of man, the son of man.

14:09.955 --> 14:12.718
He experienced humanity like all of us do.

14:13.779 --> 14:18.804
He experienced the highs, the lows, the hardships, the joys.

14:20.206 --> 14:27.794
And this is actually a great encouragement to us that the God of the universe can relate to us.

14:28.930 --> 14:32.935
First, as a son of man, we see that Jesus entered the world like every other human being.

14:33.676 --> 14:36.720
He entered like a human, he entered as a human baby.

14:36.740 --> 14:38.001
We see this in Luke chapter two.

14:38.061 --> 14:41.646
This is one of the two Christmas accounts we have in the New Testament.

14:42.607 --> 14:52.039
Verse four, Joseph also went up from the town of Nazareth in Galilee to Judea to the city of David, which is called Bethlehem because he was at the house and family line of David.

14:52.079 --> 14:53.441
We saw this in Matthew chapter one.

14:53.881 --> 14:57.746
But he did this to be registered along with Mary who was engaged to him and was pregnant.

14:58.018 --> 15:07.951
While they were there, the time came for her to give birth, and then she gave birth to her firstborn son, and she wrapped him tightly in cloth and laid him in a manger, because there was no guest room available for them.

15:09.593 --> 15:12.817
This is the picture, right, that we have of the Christmas story.

15:13.678 --> 15:22.310
And it's really crazy, if you think about it, to think that Jesus, the eternal and powerful Son of God, he entered into creation in this way.

15:23.631 --> 15:25.714
Because while babies, they are amazing gifts,

15:26.018 --> 15:28.461
and they are miracles of new life.

15:29.062 --> 15:33.707
At the same time, they are also completely helpless, right?

15:33.767 --> 15:34.368
They're needy.

15:35.469 --> 15:38.994
They cannot meet any needs that they have in and of themselves.

15:39.875 --> 15:44.721
They are completely dependent upon their parents to take care of them and to provide them for what they need.

15:44.981 --> 15:50.507
And while this is true of all of us, when we were babies, it was true of Jesus as well.

15:52.129 --> 15:55.954
One of my favorite songs we sing at Rive captures this well at the song In Christ Alone,

15:56.514 --> 16:04.905
And there's a line in that song that says this, in Christ alone, who took on flesh, fullness of God in helpless babe.

16:06.347 --> 16:08.430
Jesus entered the world like us.

16:10.012 --> 16:15.940
As the son of man, we also see that Jesus was like us, and that he experienced human limitations.

16:17.061 --> 16:26.514
That although he was fully divine, he was also fully human in the challenges he faced specifically, we see in scripture, in his suffering, but also in his temptations.

16:27.330 --> 16:29.733
Hebrews chapter two captures this well.

16:29.773 --> 16:33.017
The book of Hebrews paints this picture very well for us.

16:33.538 --> 16:34.900
But chapter two, verse 10.

16:36.061 --> 16:48.437
For in bringing many sons and daughters to glory, it was entirely appropriate that God, for whom and through whom all things exist, we saw that in John chapter one, should make the pioneer of their salvation perfect through sufferings.

16:49.399 --> 16:53.484
For the one who sanctifies and those who are sanctified all have one father.

16:53.504 --> 16:55.026
Let's jump down to verse 14.

16:55.106 --> 17:04.578
Now, since the children have flesh and blood in common, Jesus also shared in these, so that through his death, he might destroy the one holding the power of death.

17:05.159 --> 17:15.372
That is the devil, and free those who were held in slavery all their lives by the fear of death, for it is clear that he does not reach out to help angels but to help Abraham's offspring.

17:15.972 --> 17:20.498
Therefore, he had to be like his brothers and his sisters in every way

17:20.610 --> 17:27.739
so that he could become a merciful and faithful high priest and matters pertaining to God to make atonement for the sins of the people.

17:27.819 --> 17:37.030
Verse 18, for since he himself has suffered when he was tempted, he's able to help those who are tempted.

17:37.070 --> 17:49.586
Here we see that Jesus becoming like us in our humanity as the son of man that he experienced temptation early on in his ministry

17:50.146 --> 17:55.932
Jesus was let out into the wilderness by the spirit for 40 days and for 40 nights, and Jesus fasted.

17:56.633 --> 18:00.057
And after he had fasted and he was hungry, the devil showed up and he tempted him.

18:00.718 --> 18:02.379
